did.abstract: Documents, reports, publications, files, promotional material, and meeting material relating to the Hispanic Women's Network of Texas. Topics include women in business, education, health, government, and philanthropy in Texas.

bioghist.head: Administrative History
bioghist.p: The Hispanic Women's Network of Texas is a non-profit, state-wide organization formed in 1986 which seeks to address issues unique to the Hispanic population in Texas. The Hispanic Women's Network of Texas (HWNT) works to advance the educational, cultural, social, legal, and economic well-being of all women through a broader awareness of their role in society, business, and family. Members strive to celebrate the positive image and values of the Hispanic culture. Members of the HWNT advocate for Hispanic women in all aspects of life, from supporting Hispanic business women through partnerships with Texas Association of Mexican American Chambers Commerce (TAMACC), providing scholarships to Latina students, and hosting freedom marches. Among its founding women were Martha Hinojosa-Nadler, Lena Guerrero, Amalia Rodriguez-Mendoza, Mary Alice Cisneros, Christine Hernandez, and Lupe Ochoa.

The organization is headquartered in Austin, Texas and currently (as of 2022) has chapters in Austin, Corpus Christi, Dallas, El Paso, Fort Worth, Houston, the Rio Grande Valley, and San Antonio. The HWNT previously had chapters in Denton, Lubbock, and McAllen.

The HWNT has an organization-wide Board of Directors with positions including the State Chair, Treasurer, Education Chair, and State Membership Chair. Local chapters have their own organizational structure, host their own events, and each chapter has a State Representative that sits on the Board of Directors.

The HWNTâ€™s largest event is the annual State Conference, which takes place in a different Texas city each year. The conference includes networking, community building, and career advancement opportunities for Latinas across Texas.

The organization also plans events including annual board retreats; Platícas Poderosas, a lecture series; The Estrella Awards, which honors members of the HWNT that have made an outstanding impact in their communities; and the Latinas in Progress Education Program, which assists Latinas with the transition from high school to higher education.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents Note
scopecontent.p: This collection was processed in multiple parts. Part 1 includes materials donated before 2005, Part 2 includes materials donated between 2005-2018, and Part 3 includes materials donated between 2019-2021. The first acquisition includes meeting minutes, publications, conference materials, financial and administrative records, correspondence, photographs, and artifacts, 1987-2007. These materials document the founding and activities of the Hispanic Women's Network of Texas (HWNT).
Part 2: Additions

Part 2 Additions is divided into the following series: General and Administrative, Board of Directors, Committees, Conferences and Events, Collected Material, Local Chapters, Audiovisual Material, Scrapbooks, Oversize Material, Textiles, and Memorabilia.

The General and Administrative Series includes materials relating to HWNT as an organization overall. This series consists primarily of executive material, meeting agendas and notes, directories, and newsletters. This series also contains numerous versions of the HWNT standing rules and by-laws.

The Board of Directors series includes material collected by HWNT board members. The material primarily consists of financial materials such as check requests and expense reports as well as Board of Directors meeting minutes and materials from 1993-2014. The majority of this series is the material relating to the Board of Directors meetings which were typically held several times a year throughout Texas.

The Committees series is divided into the various committees constituted by the HWNT. This committees include the communications committee, the membership committee, the education committee, the executive committee, the newsletter committee, the scholarship committee, and the steering committee. The material in this series includes meeting notes, agendas, and correspondence of those committees.

The Conferences and Events series includes conference material from 1989-2014 as well as general events held by HWNT at a state-wide level from 1993-2007. Conference material primarily consists of planning materials, meeting notes, program drafts, exhibitor information, and correspondence relating to the event.

The Collected Material series includes material collected by members of HWNT that was not necessarily created for or by HWNT as an organization. This includes collected publications, invitations, newsletters, certificates, proclamations, decrees, and pamphlets.

The Local Chapters series includes material relating to the following chapters: Austin, Corpus Christi, Dallas, Denton, El Paso, Fort Worth, Houston, Lower Rio Grande Valley, Lubbock, McAllen, and San Antonio. Chapter materials include clippings, correspondence, events, meetings and agendas, newsletters, reports, and several photographs.
The Audiovisual Material series includes unlabeled photographs, floppy disks, and DAT tapes. The floppy disks in this collection contain administrative information and forms.
The Scrapbook series includes scrapbooks made by members of the Austin, Corpus Christi, and Fort Worth Chapters.
The Oversize Materials series includes oversize items such as a banner from the Fort Worth Chapter, posters, proclamations and decrees.
The Textiles series consists of various T-shirts from local chapters along with HWNT buttons and pins. This series also includes HWNT bags that were given at conferences and events.

The Memorabilia series is a collection of trophies, awards, and other items that were given at conferences. Items include paperweights, a koozie, plaques, trophies, and a key to the City of Forth Worth.
Part 3: Additions

The materials in Part 3 of the Hispanic Womenâ€™s Network of Texas collection, 1987-2019, were created and received by HWNT members as they held state and local meetings, planned and attended annual conferences, and advocated for Hispanic women in the state of Texas. The materials in this addition to the collection consist of minutes and agendas from quarterly state board meetings, invoices from events, published materials about the Latina experience in Texas and the United States, and statements on political issues.

While there are some materials from the local chapters located throughout the state of Texas (including the Austin chapter), the majority of the materials in Part 3 are those compiled by specific state board members (Guadalupe Morin, Dora Trinidad, Cecilia McKay, and Carla Romero) and consist primarily of materials from state board meetings and annual conference planning. The collection contains materials from the founding of HWNT in 1987 to 2019. The material is consistently spread between these dates, although the late 2000s and early 2010s have the least amount of material.
